    31→
    32→## Intro<a name="intro"></a>
    33→
    34→Tomli is a Python library for parsing [TOML](https://toml.io).
    35→Version 2.4.0 and later are compatible with [TOML v1.1.0](https://toml.io/en/v1.1.0).
    36→Older versions are [TOML v1.0.0](https://toml.io/en/v1.0.0) compatible.
    37→
    38→A version of Tomli, the `tomllib` module,
    39→was added to the standard library in Python 3.11
    40→via [PEP 680](https://www.python.org/dev/peps/pep-0680/).
    41→Tomli continues to provide a backport on PyPI for Python versions
    42→where the standard library module is not available
    43→and that have not yet reached their end-of-life.
    44→
    45→Tomli uses [mypyc](https://github.com/mypyc/mypyc)
    46→to generate binary wheels for most of the widely used platforms,
    47→so Python 3.11+ users may prefer it over `tomllib` for improved performance.
    48→Pure Python wheels are available on any platform and should perform the same as `tomllib`.
    49→
    50→## Installation<a name="installation"></a>
    51→
    52→```bash
    53→pip install tomli
    54→```
    55→
    56→## Usage<a name="usage"></a>
    57→
    58→### Parse a TOML string<a name="parse-a-toml-string"></a>
    59→
    60→```python
    61→import tomli
    62→
    63→toml_str = """
    64→[[players]]
    65→name = "Lehtinen"
    66→number = 26
    67→
    68→[[players]]
    69→name = "Numminen"
    70→number = 27
    71→"""
    72→
    73→toml_dict = tomli.loads(toml_str)
    74→assert toml_dict == {
    75→    "players": [{"name": "Lehtinen", "number": 26}, {"name": "Numminen", "number": 27}]
    76→}
    77→```
    78→
    79→### Parse a TOML file<a name="parse-a-toml-file"></a>
    80→
    81→```python
    82→import tomli
    83→
    84→with open("path_to_file/conf.toml", "rb") as f:
    85→    toml_dict = tomli.load(f)
    86→```
    87→
    88→The file must be opened in binary mode (with the `"rb"` flag).
    89→Binary mode will enforce decoding the file as UTF-8 with universal newlines disabled,
    90→both of which are required to correctly parse TOML.
    91→
    92→### Handle invalid TOML<a name="handle-invalid-toml"></a>
    93→
    94→```python
    95→import tomli
    96→
    97→try:
    98→    toml_dict = tomli.loads("]] this is invalid TOML [[")
    99→except tomli.TOMLDecodeError:
   100→    print("Yep, definitely not valid.")
   101→```
   102→
   103→Note that error messages are considered informational only.
   104→They should not be assumed to stay constant across Tomli versions.
   105→
   106→### Construct `decimal.Decimal`s from TOML floats<a name="construct-decimaldecimals-from-toml-floats"></a>
   107→
   108→```python
   109→from decimal import Decimal
   110→import tomli
   111→
   112→toml_dict = tomli.loads("precision-matters = 0.982492", parse_float=Decimal)
   113→assert isinstance(toml_dict["precision-matters"], Decimal)
   114→assert toml_dict["precision-matters"] == Decimal("0.982492")
   115→```
   116→
   117→Note that `decimal.Decimal` can be replaced with another callable that converts a TOML float from string to a Python type.
   118→The `decimal.Decimal` is, however, a practical choice for use cases where float inaccuracies can not be tolerated.
   119→
   120→Illegal types are `dict` and `list`, and their subtypes.
   121→A `ValueError` will be raised if `parse_float` produces illegal types.
   122→
   123→### Building a `tomli`/`tomllib` compatibility layer<a name="building-a-tomlitomllib-compatibility-layer"></a>
   124→
   125→Python versions 3.11+ ship with a version of Tomli:
   126→the `tomllib` standard library module.
   127→To build code that uses the standard library if available,
   128→but still works seamlessly with Python 3.6+,
   129→do the following.
   130→
   131→Instead of a hard Tomli dependency, use the following
   132→[dependency specifier](https://packaging.python.org/en/latest/specifications/dependency-specifiers/)
   133→to only require Tomli when the standard library module is not available:
   134→
   135→```
   136→tomli >= 1.1.0 ; python_version < "3.11"
   137→```
   138→
   139→Then, in your code, import a TOML parser using the following fallback mechanism:
   140→
   141→```python
   142→import sys
   143→
   144→if sys.version_info >= (3, 11):
   145→    import tomllib
   146→else:
   147→    import tomli as tomllib
   148→
   149→tomllib.loads("['This parses fine with Python 3.6+']")
   150→```
   151→
   152→## FAQ<a name="faq"></a>
   153→
   154→### Why this parser?<a name="why-this-parser"></a>
   155→
   156→- it's lil'
   157→- pure Python with zero dependencies
   158→- the fastest pure Python parser [\*](#pure-python):
   159→  14x as fast as [tomlkit](https://pypi.org/project/tomlkit/),
   160→  2.1x as fast as [toml](https://pypi.org/project/toml/)
   161→- outputs [basic data types](#how-do-toml-types-map-into-python-types) only
   162→- 100% spec compliant: passes all tests in
   163→  [toml-lang/toml-test](https://github.com/toml-lang/toml-test)
   164→  test suite
   165→- thoroughly tested: 100% branch coverage
   166→
   167→### Is comment preserving round-trip parsing supported?<a name="is-comment-preserving-round-trip-parsing-supported"></a>
   168→
   169→No.
   170→
   171→The `tomli.loads` function returns a plain `dict` that is populated with builtin types and types from the standard library only.
   172→Preserving comments requires a custom type to be returned so will not be supported,
   173→at least not by the `tomli.loads` and `tomli.load` functions.
   174→
   175→Look into [TOML Kit](https://github.com/sdispater/tomlkit) if preservation of style is what you need.
   176→
   177→### Is there a `dumps`, `write` or `encode` function?<a name="is-there-a-dumps-write-or-encode-function"></a>
   178→
   179→[Tomli-W](https://github.com/hukkin/tomli-w) is the write-only counterpart of Tomli, providing `dump` and `dumps` functions.
   180→
   181→The core library does not include write capability, as most TOML use cases are read-only, and Tomli intends to be minimal.
   182→
   183→### How do TOML types map into Python types?<a name="how-do-toml-types-map-into-python-types"></a>
   184→
   185→| TOML type        | Python type         | Details                                                      |
   186→| ---------------- | ------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
   187→| Document Root    | `dict`              |                                                              |
   188→| Key              | `str`               |                                                              |
   189→| String           | `str`               |                                                              |
   190→| Integer          | `int`               |                                                              |
   191→| Float            | `float`             |                                                              |
   192→| Boolean          | `bool`              |                                                              |
   193→| Offset Date-Time | `datetime.datetime` | `tzinfo` attribute set to an instance of `datetime.timezone` |
   194→| Local Date-Time  | `datetime.datetime` | `tzinfo` attribute set to `None`                             |
   195→| Local Date       | `datetime.date`     |                                                              |
   196→| Local Time       | `datetime.time`     |                                                              |
   197→| Array            | `list`              |                                                              |
   198→| Table            | `dict`              |                                                              |
   199→| Inline Table     | `dict`              |                                                              |
   200→
   201→## Performance<a name="performance"></a>
   202→
   203→The `benchmark/` folder in this repository contains a performance benchmark for comparing the various Python TOML parsers.
   204→
   205→Below are the results for commit [064e492](https://github.com/hukkin/tomli/tree/064e492919b2338def788753b8c981c9131334c0).
   206→
   207→### Mypyc generated wheel<a name="mypyc-generated-wheel"></a>
   208→
   209→```console
   210→foo@bar:~/dev/tomli$ python --version
   211→Python 3.14.2
   212→foo@bar:~/dev/tomli$ pip freeze
   213→pytomlpp==1.1.0
   214→rtoml==0.13.0
   215→toml==0.10.2
   216→tomli @ file:///home/foo/dev/tomli
   217→tomlkit==0.13.3
   218→foo@bar:~/dev/tomli$ python benchmark/run.py
   219→Parsing data.toml 5000 times:
   220→------------------------------------------------------
   221→    parser |  exec time | performance (more is better)
   222→-----------+------------+-----------------------------
   223→     rtoml |    0.328 s | baseline (100%)
   224→  pytomlpp |    0.365 s | 89.75%
   225→     tomli |    0.838 s | 39.12%
   226→      toml |     3.01 s | 10.90%
   227→   tomlkit |     20.7 s | 1.59%
   228→```
   229→
   230→### Pure Python<a name="pure-python"></a>
   231→
   232→```console
   233→foo@bar:~/dev/tomli$ python benchmark/run.py
   234→Parsing data.toml 5000 times:
   235→------------------------------------------------------
   236→    parser |  exec time | performance (more is better)
   237→-----------+------------+-----------------------------
   238→     rtoml |    0.323 s | baseline (100%)
   239→  pytomlpp |    0.365 s | 88.40%
   240→     tomli |     1.44 s | 22.36%
   241→      toml |     3.03 s | 10.65%
   242→   tomlkit |     20.6 s | 1.57%
   243→```
